      "content": "It is true that some economic models and targeted studies demonstrate that certain benefit structures can create reservation wages that are higher than the pay offered by low-wage jobs. These findings highlight the concept of \"benefit cliffs,\" where earning slightly more income leads to a disproportionate loss of benefits. However, these studies usually point to the *design* of the benefits—not the existence of them—as the primary driver of reduced participation.",
